ce:section.ce:para:
Fig. 4
a shows the discharge performances of coin cells with LiCoO2, LiCoO2/mRGO, LiCoO2/pRGO, LiCoO2/GQDs as cathodes measured at various discharge rates. Obviously, all three composites exhibit higher specific capacity and better rate capability than the bare LiCoO2, which demonstrate that the graphene with different lateral size and basal plane morphologies could enhance the electrochemical properties of LiCoO2. The initial discharge capacities of the cells with LiCoO2/mRGO, LiCoO2/pRGO, LiCoO2/GQDs cathodes can reach to 228, 225.1, 184 mAh g−1 at 0.2 C, and decrease to 106, 84.8, 43.3 mAh g−1 at 5 C, but get back to 208.7, 185.5, 140.5 mAh g−1 once the discharge rate return to 0.2 C. The reason is that once the charge/discharge rate is of 5 C, the charge/discharge time is quite short, and the inherent electron/ion conductivities of the LiCoO2 cathode are both relatively low, thus, there is no enough Li ions can be insert into/extract from the LiCoO2, and its apparent capacity is close to zero. When the charge/discharge rate is decreased to 0.2 C, the capacity can be recovered partially due might to the structure of LiCoO2 has been destroyed somehow. These data reveal in general that even the lateral sizes of mRGO and GQDs, and the basal plane morphologies of mRGO and pRGO are different, but all they can improve somehow the electrochemical properties of LiCoO2. More specifically, it can be found that although both cells with LiCoO2/mRGO and LiCoO2/pRGO as cathodes have almost the same specific capacity at the beginning, the one of the LiCoO2/pRGO decrease quicker than that of LiCoO2/mRGO with the discharge rate increasing, which may raise from the basal plane difference between the mRGO and pRGO, precisely, the nanopores on basal planes of pRGO most probably decrease the electron and/or ion conductivity. The reason might be that the nanopores in pRGO are defects intrinsically and could destroy the π-π structure of mRGO, which affect the overall physical/chemical properties of pRGO, especially the electron and ion conductivity [40–42]. Notably, LiCoO2/mRGO shows better electrochemical performance over the LiCoO2/GQDs demonstrating the lateral size the graphene is also crucial. The reason is that the mRGO can cover larger portion of the surfaces of LiCoO2 particles and also form network bridges among them that can enhance the electron and Li+ diffusion on the LiCoO2 surface and also among the particles. This also affects their cycling stability. As shown in Fig. 4b, after 500 charge/discharge cycles, the cell using LiCoO2/mRGO cathode retains higher specific capacitance than those of LiCoO2/pRGO and LiCoO2/GQDs (Table 1
). By comparing the SEM images before and after the charge/discharge cycle, a thin homogeneous CEI (cathode electrolyte interphase) film seems formed on the LiCoO2/mRGO, LiCoO2/pRGO [34,43]. Clearly, both mRGO and pRGO can promote the CEI film formation on LiCoO2 that may protect its pulverization, and thereby enhance the cycling stability of LiCoO2/mRGO, LiCoO2/pRGO cathodes [34] (see Fig. 5).
